Section 7.2 Addition and Subtraction Identities In this section, we begin expanding our repertoire of trigonometric identities. The sum and difference identities \[\cos (\alpha - eta )=\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] \[\cos (\alpha + eta )=\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] \[\sin (\alpha + eta )=\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\cos (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] \[\sin (\alpha - eta )=\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-\cos (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] We will prove the difference of angles identity for cosine. The rest of the identities can be derived from this one. Proof of the difference of angles identity for cosine Consider two points on a unit circle: \(P\) at an angle of \(\alpha\) from the positive \(x\) axis with coordinates \(\left(\cos (\alpha ),\sin (\alpha )ight)\), and \(Q\) at an angle of \( eta\) with coordinates \(\left(\cos ( eta ),\sin ( eta)ight)\). Notice the measure of angle \(POQ\) is \(\alpha\) – \( eta\). Label two more points: \(C\) at an angle of \(\alpha\) – \( eta\), with coordinates \(\left(\cos (\alpha - eta ),\sin (\alpha - eta )ight)\), \(D\) at the point (1, 0). Notice that the distance from \(C\) to \(D\) is the same as the distance from \(P\) to \(Q\) because triangle \(COD\) is a rotation of triangle \(POQ\). Using the distance formula to find the distance from \(P\) to \(Q\) yields \[\sqrt{\left(\cos (\alpha )-\cos ( eta )ight)^{2} +\left(\sin (\alpha )-\sin ( eta )ight)^{2} }
onumber\] Expanding this \[\sqrt{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\cos ^{2} ( eta )+\sin ^{2} (\alpha )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )+\sin ^{2} ( eta )}
onumber\] Applying the Pythagorean Identity and simplifying \[\sqrt{2-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )}
onumber\] Similarly, using the distance formula to find the distance from \(C\) to \(D\) \[\sqrt{\left(\cos (\alpha - eta )-1ight)^{2} +\left(\sin (\alpha - eta )-0ight)^{2} }
onumber\] Expanding this \[\sqrt{\cos ^{2} (\alpha - eta )-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+1+\sin ^{2} (\alpha - eta )}
onumber\] Applying the Pythagorean Identity and simplifying \[\sqrt{-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+2}
onumber\] Since the two distances are the same we set these two formulas equal to each other and simplify \[\sqrt{2-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )} =\sqrt{-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+2}
onumber\] \[2-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )=-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+2
onumber\] \[\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )=\cos (\alpha - eta )
onumber\] This establishes the identity. Exercise \(\PageIndex{1}\) By writing \(\cos (\alpha + eta )\) as \(\cos \left(\alpha -\left(- eta ight)ight)\), show the sum of angles identity for cosine follows from the difference of angles identity proven above. Answer \[ egin{array}{l} {\cos (\alpha + eta )=\cos (\alpha -(- eta ))} \ {\cos (\alpha )\cos (- eta )+\sin (\alpha )\sin (- eta )} \ {\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\sin (\alpha )(-\sin ( eta ))} \ {\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )} \end{array}
onumber\] The sum and difference of angles identities are often used to rewrite expressions in other forms, or to rewrite an angle in terms of simpler angles. Exercise \(\PageIndex{2}\) Find the exact value of \(\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)\). Answer \[\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)=\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{3} -\dfrac{\pi }{4} ight)=\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{3} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi }{4} ight)-\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi }{3} ight)\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{4} ight)
onumber\] \[=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} -\dfrac{1}{2} \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2}\quad \dfrac{\sqrt{6} -\sqrt{2} }{4}
onumber\] Additionally, these identities can be used to simplify expressions or prove new identities These identities can also be used to solve equations. Combining Waves of Equal Period A sinusoidal function of the form \(f(x)=A\sin (Bx+C)\) can be rewritten using the sum of angles identity. Notice that the result is a stretch of the sine added to a different stretch of the cosine, but both have the same horizontal compression, which results in the same period. We might ask now whether this process can be reversed – can a combination of a sine and cosine of the same period be written as a single sinusoidal function? To explore this, we will look in general at the procedure used in the example above. \[f(x)=A\sin (Bx+C)
onumber\]Use the sum of angles identity \[=A\left(\sin (Bx)\cos (C)+\cos (Bx)\sin (C)ight)
onumber\]Distribute the \(A\) \[=A\sin (Bx)\cos (C)+A\cos (Bx)\sin (C)
onumber\]Rearrange the terms a bit \[=A\cos (C)\sin (Bx)+A\sin (C)\cos (Bx)
onumber\] Based on this result, if we have an expression of the form \(m\sin (Bx)+n\cos (Bx)\), we could rewrite it as a single sinusoidal function if we can find values A and C so that \(m\sin (Bx)+n\cos (Bx)\) \(=A\cos (C)\sin (Bx)+A\sin (C)\cos (Bx)\), which will require that: \[ egin{array}{l} {m=A\cos (C)} \ {n=A\sin (C)} \end{array}
onumber\] which can be rewritten as \[ egin{array}{l} {\dfrac{m}{A} =\cos (C)} \ {\dfrac{n}{A} =\sin (C)} \end{array}
onumber\] To find \(A\), \[m^{2} +n^{2} =\left(A\cos (C)ight)^{2} +\left(A\sin (C)ight)^{2}
onumber\] \[=A^{2} \cos ^{2} (C)+A^{2} \sin ^{2} (C)
onumber\] \[=A^{2} \left(\cos ^{2} (C)+\sin ^{2} (C)ight)
onumber\]Apply the Pythagorean Identity and simplify \[=A^{2}
onumber\] REWRITING A SUM OF SINE AND COSINE AS A SINGLE SINE To rewrite \(m\sin (Bx)+n\cos (Bx)\) as \(A\sin (Bx+C)\) \[A^{2} =m^{2} +n^{2}\quad \cos (C)=\dfrac{m}{A}	ext{ and }\sin (C)=\dfrac{n}{A}\] You can use either of the last two equations to solve for possible values of C . Since there will usually be two possible solutions, we will need to look at both to determine which quadrant C is in and determine which solution for C satisfies both equations. Exercise \(\PageIndex{3}\) Rewrite \(-3\sqrt{2} \sin (5x)+3\sqrt{2} \cos (5x)\) as a single sinusoidal function. Answer \[A^{2} =\left(-3\sqrt{2} ight)^{2} +\left(3\sqrt{2} ight)^{2} =36\quad A=6
onumber\] \[\cos (C)=\dfrac{-3\sqrt{2} }{6} =\dfrac{-\sqrt{2} }{2}\quad \sin (C)=\dfrac{3\sqrt{2} }{6} =\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2}\quad C=\dfrac{3\pi }{4}
onumber\] \[6\sin \left(5x+\dfrac{3\pi }{4} ight)
onumber\] Rewriting a combination of sine and cosine of equal periods as a single sinusoidal function provides an approach for solving some equations. The Product-to-Sum and Sum-to-Product Identities The Product-to-Sum Identities \[ egin{array}{l} {\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\sin (\alpha + eta )+\sin (\alpha - eta )ight)} \ {\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\cos (\alpha - eta )-\cos (\alpha + eta )ight)} \ {\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\cos (\alpha + eta )+\cos (\alpha - eta )ight)} \end{array}\] We will prove the first of these, using the sum and difference of angles identities from the beginning of the section. The proofs of the other two identities are similar and are left as an exercise. Proof of the product-to-sum identity for sin(\(\alpha\))cos(\( eta\)) Recall the sum and difference of angles identities from earlier \[\sin (\alpha + eta )=\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\cos (\alpha )\sin ( eta )
onumber\] \[\sin (\alpha - eta )=\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-\cos (\alpha )\sin ( eta )
onumber\] Adding these two equations, we obtain \[\sin (\alpha + eta )+\sin (\alpha - eta )=2\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )
onumber\] Dividing by 2, we establish the identity \[\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\sin (\alpha + eta )+\sin (\alpha - eta )ight)
onumber\] Exercise \(\PageIndex{4}\) Evaluate \(\cos \left(\dfrac{11\pi }{12} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)\). Answer \[\cos \left(\dfrac{11\pi }{12} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\cos \left(\dfrac{11\pi }{12} +\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)+\cos \left(\dfrac{11\pi }{12} -\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)ight)
onumber\] \[=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\cos \left(\pi ight)+\cos \left(\dfrac{5\pi }{6} ight)ight)=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(-1-\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} ight)
onumber\] \[=\dfrac{-2-\sqrt{3} }{4}
onumber\] The Sum-to-Product Identities \[\sin \left(uight)+\sin \left(vight)=2\sin \left(\dfrac{u+v}{2} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{u-v}{2} ight)\] \[\sin \left(uight)-\sin \left(vight)=2\sin \left(\dfrac{u-v}{2} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{u+v}{2} ight)\] \[\cos \left(uight)+\cos \left(vight)=2\cos \left(\dfrac{u+v}{2} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{u-v}{2} ight)\] \[\cos \left(uight)-\cos \left(vight)=-2\sin \left(\dfrac{u+v}{2} ight)\sin \left(\dfrac{u-v}{2} ight)\] We will again prove one of these and leave the rest as an exercise. Proof of the sum-to-product identity for sine function We define two new variables: \[ egin{array}{l} {u=\alpha + eta } \ {v=\alpha - eta } \end{array}
onumber\] Adding these equations yields \(u+v=2\alpha\), giving \(\alpha =\dfrac{u+v}{2}\) Subtracting the equations yields \(u-v=2 eta\), or \( eta =\dfrac{u-v}{2}\) Substituting these expressions into the product-to-sum identity \[\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\sin (\alpha + eta )+\sin (\alpha - eta )ight)
onumber\]gives \[\sin \left(\dfrac{u+v}{2} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{u-v}{2} ight)=\dfrac{1}{2} \left(\sin \left(uight)+\sin \left(vight)ight)
onumber\]Multiply by 2 on both sides \[2\sin \left(\dfrac{u+v}{2} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{u-v}{2} ight)=\sin \left(uight)+\sin \left(vight)
onumber\]Establishing the identity Exercise \(\PageIndex{5}\) Notice that, using the negative angle identity, \(\sin \left(uight)-\sin \left(vight)=\sin (u)+\sin (-v)\). Use this along with the sum of sines identity to prove the sum-to-product identity for \(\sin \left(uight)-\sin \left(vight)\). Answer \[\sin (u)-\sin (v)
onumber\]Use negative angle identity for sine \[\sin (u) + \sin (-v)
onumber\]Use sum-to-product identity for sine \[2	ext{sin} (\dfrac{u + (-v)}{2}) 	ext{cos} (\dfrac{u - (-v)}{2})
onumber\]Eliminate the parenthesis \[2	ext{sin} (\dfrac{u - v}{2}) 	ext{cos} (\dfrac{u + v}{2})
onumber\]Establishing the identity Important Topics of This Section The sum and difference identities Combining waves of equal periods Product-to-sum identities Sum-to-product identities Completing proofs

