Example \(\PageIndex{1}\) Find the exact value of \(\cos (75{}^\circ )\). Solution Since \(75{}^\circ =30{}^\circ +45{}^\circ\), we can evaluate \(\cos (75{}^\circ )\) as \[\cos (75{}^\circ )=\cos (30{}^\circ +45{}^\circ )
onumber\] Apply the cosine sum of angles identity \[=\cos (30{}^\circ )\cos (45{}^\circ )-\sin (30{}^\circ )\sin (45{}^\circ )
onumber\] Evaluate \[=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} \cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} -\dfrac{1}{2} \cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2}
onumber\] Simply \[=\dfrac{\sqrt{6} -\sqrt{2} }{4}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) Prove \(\dfrac{\sin (a+b)}{\sin (a-b)} =\dfrac{	an (a)+	an (b)}{	an (a)-	an (b)}\). Solution As with any identity, we need to first decide which side to begin with. Since the left side involves sum and difference of angles, we might start there \[\dfrac{\sin (a+b)}{\sin (a-b)}
onumber\] Apply the sum and difference of angle identities \[=\dfrac{\sin (a)\cos (b)+\cos (a)\sin (b)}{\sin (a)\cos (b)-\cos (a)\sin (b)}
onumber\] Since it is not immediately obvious how to proceed, we might start on the other side, and see if the path is more apparent. \[\dfrac{	an (a)+	an (b)}{	an (a)-	an (b)}
onumber\] Rewriting the tangents using the tangent identity \[=\dfrac{\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} +\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} }{\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} -\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} }
onumber\]Multiplying the top and bottom by cos(\(a\))cos(\(b\)) \[=\dfrac{\left(\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} +\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} ight)\cos (a)\cos (b)}{\left(\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} -\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} ight)\cos (a)\cos (b)}
onumber\]Distributing and simplifying \[=\dfrac{\sin (a)\cos (b)+\sin (b)\cos (a)}{\sin (a)\cos (b)-\sin (b)\cos (a)}
onumber\]From above, we recognize this \[=\dfrac{\sin (a+b)}{\sin (a-b)}
onumber\]Establishing the identity

Example \(\PageIndex{4}\) Solve \(\sin (x)\sin (2x)+\cos (x)\cos (2x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}\). Solution By recognizing the left side of the equation as the result of the difference of angles identity for cosine, we can simplify the equation \[\sin (x)\sin (2x)+\cos (x)\cos (2x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\]Apply the difference of angles identity \[\cos (x-2x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\] \[\cos (-x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\]Use the negative angle identity \[\cos (x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\] Since this is a special cosine value we recognize from the unit circle, we can quickly write the answers: \[ egin{array}{l} {x=\dfrac{\pi }{6} +2\pi k} \ {x=\dfrac{11\pi }{6} +2\pi k} \end{array}
onumber\], where \(k\) is an integer

Example \(\PageIndex{7}\) Solve \(3\sin (2x)+4\cos (2x)=1\) to find two positive solutions. Solution Since the sine and cosine have the same period, we can rewrite them as a single sinusoidal function. \[A^{2} =\left(3ight)^{2} +\left(4ight)^{2} =25	ext{ so }A = 5
onumber\] \[\cos (C)=\dfrac{3}{5}	ext{ so }C=\cos ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{3}{5} ight)\approx 0.927	ext{ or }C=2\pi -0.927=5.356
onumber\] Since \(\sin (C)=\dfrac{4}{5}\), a positive value, we need the angle in the first quadrant, \(C = 0.927\). Using this, our equation becomes \[5\sin \left(2x+0.927ight)=1
onumber\] Divide by 5 \[\sin \left(2x+0.927ight)=\dfrac{1}{5}
onumber\] Make the substitution \(u = 2x + 0.927\) \[\sin \left(uight)=\dfrac{1}{5}
onumber\]The inverse gives a first solution \[u=\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{1}{5} ight)\approx 0.201
onumber\] By symmetry, the second solution is \[u=\pi -0.201=2.940
onumber\] A third solution would be \[u=2\pi +0.201=6.485
onumber\] Undoing the substitution, we can find two positive solutions for \(x\). \[ egin{array}{ccccc}{2x+0.927=0.201}&{	ext{or}}&{2x+0.927=2.940}&{	ext{or}}&{2x+0.927=6.485}\{2x=-0.726}&{}&{2x=2.013}&{}&{2x=5.558}\{x=-0.363}&{}&{x=1.007}&{}&{x=2.779}\end{array}
onumber\] Since the first of these is negative, we eliminate it and keep the two positive solutions, \(x=1.007\) and \(x=2.779\).

Example \(\PageIndex{10}\) Prove the identity \(\dfrac{\cos (4t)-\cos (2t)}{\sin (4t)+\sin (2t)} =-	an (t)\). Solution Since the left side seems more complicated, we can start there and simplify. \[\dfrac{\cos (4t)-\cos (2t)}{\sin (4t)+\sin (2t)}
onumber\]Use the sum-to-product identities \[=\dfrac{-2\sin \left(\dfrac{4t+2t}{2} ight)\sin \left(\dfrac{4t-2t}{2} ight)}{2\sin \left(\dfrac{4t+2t}{2} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{4t-2t}{2} ight)}
onumber\]Simplify \[=\dfrac{-2\sin \left(3tight)\sin \left(tight)}{2\sin \left(3tight)\cos \left(tight)}
onumber\]Simplify further \[=\dfrac{-\sin \left(tight)}{\cos \left(tight)}
onumber\]Rewrite as a tangent \[=-	an (t)
onumber\]Establishing the identity

Example \(\PageIndex{11}\) Solve \(\sin \left(\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)+\sin \left(3\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)=\cos (\pi {\kern 1pt} t)\) for all solutions with \(0\le t<2\). Solution In an equation like th is, it is not immediately obvious how to proceed. One option would be to combine the two sine functions on the left side of the equation. Another would be to move the cosine to the left side of the equation, and combine it with one of the sines. For no particularly good reason, we’ll begin by combining the sines on the left side of the equation and see how things work out. \[\sin \left(\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)+\sin \left(3\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)=\cos (\pi {\kern 1pt} t)
onumber\]Apply the sum to product identity on the left \[2\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi {\kern 1pt} t+3\pi {\kern 1pt} t}{2} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi {\kern 1pt} t-3\pi {\kern 1pt} t}{2} ight)=\cos (\pi {\kern 1pt} t)
onumber\]Simplify \[2\sin \left(2\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)\cos \left(-\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)=\cos (\pi {\kern 1pt} t)
onumber\]Apply the negative angle identity \[2\sin \left(2\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)\cos \left(\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)=\cos (\pi {\kern 1pt} t)
onumber\]Rearrange the equation to be 0 on one side \[2\sin \left(2\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)\cos \left(\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)-\cos (\pi {\kern 1pt} t)=0
onumber\]Factor out the cosine \[\cos \left(\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)\left(2\sin \left(2\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)-1ight)=0
onumber\] Using the Zero Product Theorem we know that at least one of the two factors must be zero. The first factor, \(\cos \left(\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)\), has period \(P=\dfrac{2\pi }{\pi } =2\), so the solution interval of \(0\le t<2\) represents one full cycle of this function. \[\cos \left(\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)=0
onumber\]Substitute \(u=\pi {\kern 1pt} t\) \[\cos \left(uight)=0
onumber\]On one cycle, this has solutions \[u=\dfrac{\pi }{2}	ext{ or }u=\dfrac{3\pi }{2}
onumber\]Undo the substitution \[\pi {\kern 1pt} t=\dfrac{\pi }{2}	ext{, so }t=\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\] \[\pi {\kern 1pt} t=\dfrac{3\pi }{2}	ext{, so }t=\dfrac{3}{2}
onumber\] The second factor, \(2\sin \left(2\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)-1\), has period of \(P=\dfrac{2\pi }{2\pi } =1\), so the solution interval \(0\le t<2\) contains two complete cycles of this function. \[2\sin \left(2\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)-1=0
onumber\] Isolate the sine \[\sin \left(2\pi {\kern 1pt} tight)=\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\] Substitute \(u=2\pi {\kern 1pt} t\) \[\sin (u)=\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\] On one cycle, this has solutions \[u=\dfrac{\pi }{6}	ext{ or }u=\dfrac{5\pi }{6}
onumber\] On the second cycle, the solutions are \[u=2\pi +\dfrac{\pi }{6} =\dfrac{13\pi }{6}	ext{ or }u=2\pi +\dfrac{5\pi }{6} =\dfrac{17\pi }{6}
onumber\] Undo the substitution \[2\pi {\kern 1pt} t=\dfrac{\pi }{6}	ext{, so }t=\dfrac{1}{12}
onumber\] \[2\pi {\kern 1pt} t=\dfrac{5\pi }{6}	ext{, so }t=\dfrac{5}{12}
onumber\] \[2\pi {\kern 1pt} t=\dfrac{13\pi }{6}	ext{, so }t=\dfrac{13}{12}
onumber\] \[2\pi {\kern 1pt} t=\dfrac{17\pi }{6}	ext{, so }t=\dfrac{17}{12}
onumber\] Altogether, we found six solutions on \(0\le t<2\), which we can confirm by looking at the graph. \[t=\dfrac{1}{12} ,\dfrac{5}{12} ,\dfrac{1}{2} ,\dfrac{13}{12} ,\dfrac{3}{2} ,\dfrac{17}{12}
onumber\]

